    <item>
      <title>rsvn&#39;s Blog</title>
      <link>https://risvn.github.io/blog/posts/whyblog/</link>
      <pubDate>Thu, 30 Oct 2025 18:12:28 +0530</pubDate>
      <guid>https://risvn.github.io/blog/posts/whyblog/</guid>
      <description>&lt;h3 id=&#34;about&#34;&gt;About&lt;/h3&gt;
&lt;blockquote&gt;
&lt;p&gt;“Your mind is for having ideas, not holding them.”&lt;br&gt;
— &lt;em&gt;David Allen&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;/blockquote&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Our brain consumes far more information than we can handle — and often, we forget things( these are the words form the book &lt;strong&gt;bulidng a  second brain&lt;/strong&gt;)&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;So, I wanted to make my learning &lt;strong&gt;structured&lt;/strong&gt; — something easily maintainable, reachable, and organized.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;This is &lt;em&gt;my commonplace&lt;/em&gt; — a space to store the information I gather and interpret in my own perspective and can be accesed from any where just with internet connection.&lt;/p&gt;</description>
    </item>
    <item>
      <title>self hosting</title>
      <link>https://risvn.github.io/blog/posts/daemon/</link>
      <pubDate>Fri, 07 Nov 2025 17:35:23 +0530</pubDate>
      <guid>https://risvn.github.io/blog/posts/daemon/</guid>
      <description>&lt;blockquote&gt;
&lt;p&gt;If you need a machine and don’t buy it,
then you will ultimately find that you have paid for it and don’t have it.&lt;br&gt;
— &lt;em&gt;Henry Ford via Clayton Christensen&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;/blockquote&gt;
&lt;p&gt;These days I&amp;rsquo;m working on an &lt;strong&gt;HTTP server in C&lt;/strong&gt; using &lt;strong&gt;WebSockets&lt;/strong&gt;, just to get a taste of how things work under the hood.&lt;br&gt;
The only functionality of the server is to listen and send HTML and media files.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;hr&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Now a days &lt;strong&gt;cloud&lt;/strong&gt; is more popularized for its &lt;strong&gt;accessibility&lt;/strong&gt;, &lt;strong&gt;scalability&lt;/strong&gt;, and the fact that &lt;strong&gt;real hardware is abstracted away&lt;/strong&gt; from developers.&lt;br&gt;
I wanted to see for myself what it’s like to &lt;strong&gt;self-host on a bare-metal server&lt;/strong&gt; — even though it’s a small project.&lt;br&gt;
At this point, my servers are sitting idle anyway, so why not?&lt;/p&gt;</description>
    </item>
